      "strengths_deep_dive": [
        "EJI's strength lies in its dual-track approach of direct legal service and systemic change. While providing <cite id=\"2\">legal assistance to the condemned</cite>, they simultaneously manage <cite id=\"12\">$50,375,000 in total grants</cite> to partner organizations, including a <cite id=\"13\">$30,000,000 grant to the Legacy Foundation</cite>. This grantmaking capacity, combined with a <cite id=\"14\">perfect 100/100 Leadership score</cite> from Charity Navigator, positions EJI as a central pillar in the American civil rights landscape."
      ],
      "summary": "Founded in <cite id=\"1\">1989</cite>, the Equal Justice Initiative (EJI) is a Montgomery-based nonprofit committed to ending mass incarceration and excessive punishment in the United States. The organization provides <cite id=\"2\">legal representation to the poor, the incarcerated, and the condemned</cite>, specifically those facing execution or extreme punishment. EJI's work extends beyond the courtroom into public education and racial justice, maintaining a <cite id=\"3\">97/100 overall score from Charity Navigator</cite>. Financially, the organization is exceptionally lean, reporting <cite id=\"4\">$67,268,484 in total revenue</cite> for the 2023 tax year with a <cite id=\"5\">96.9% program expense ratio</cite>. This efficiency is further highlighted by a <cite id=\"6\">fundraising efficiency of $0.00 per $1 raised</cite>, indicating that EJI covers its development costs through investment income or other non-donation streams. Their impact is tangible; in 2025 alone, the organization reported <cite id=\"7\">37 death row commutations</cite> and provided support to <cite id=\"8\">7,200 families</cite>. EJI also operates a health clinic and a <cite id=\"9\">mobile grocery</cite> to address the intersection of poverty and justice in Alabama.",
